Nov 24 2009 	Outstanding Hotel	By far the best Hotel I had ever been to, great staff, great service and an even better Buffet. You dont even have to leave the Hotel, food, games everything is right there. Outstanding!!!!	
Nov 20 2009 	Great Place to Stay!!!	We got a room on the 6th floor (top floor) in the Spa Tower. If you are going to stay here, I would suggest the Spa Tower, unless you have kids, then the other tower would be for you. The Room: We walked in our room and it was fabulous! At night we had a great view of the city. There were french doors that opened up to a grass/garden area. It wasn't a balcony, it was french doors that just opened up with a balcony railing right when you open the door. There were a couple sitting chairs and a coffee table that were right next to the french doors, so you can open the doors and sit in the chairs and relax. There is an ethernet cable ready for you to plug your computer into and it was free. The desk is nice sized with an office chair. The bed was really nice. Very comfortable and not too hard. There is a walk-in closet (nice-sized) with an ironing board, iron, and a safe. There is a little bar area that has a mini coffee maker. It makes single cups of coffee at a time. There is a little box where you can choose your coffee, tea, etc.. The Bathroom: The bathroom is BIG! There is a corner jacuzzi tub that can easily fit 2 people. There is a corner shower stall that has a sitting area and you can choose between a regular shower head or the waterfall shower head. Dual sinks with great ammenities. (shampoo, conditioner, shower gel, lotion, q-tips, cotton nalls, etc.). The toilet is in a seperate part of the bathroom and is seperated by a door. There is a knob in the bathroom that you can turn on to listen to whatever you are watching on TV. I guess it's good if you're listening to the news while getting ready or whatever. The room includes some really nice and comfy robes. Dislike: The only thing I did not like was that there was no fridge in the room. As nice as the rooms are, there was no fridge. Kinda weird. In place of a fridge was what they consider a &quot;cooler&quot;. This thing is not a cooler and you cannot change the temp of it. They have a bottle of water in there ($5 for the bottle) and it was maybe 2 degrees over room temp. Pretty pathetic cooler. There is a sign though that says that if you would like to request a fridge brought up to the room you can do so, but for only certain rooms. Again, weird.The Pool: The pool is gorgeous! Unfortunately I was unable to go there.The Spa: The Spa is awesome! A little pricey, but well worth the money. I got massages, scrubs, etc.. You get a robe and slippers, a private locker and it is just absolutely relaxing. There is a sauna and a steam room, hot and cold plunges, and a little pool inside the locker room. There is also these showers that have water plunging down on you really hard. Kinda massages your back and stuff. There are normal showers in there as well with the waterfall nozzle. They have large bottles of shampoo, conditioner, and shower gel for you to use. There is also a fitness center in it, so you can work out too. I ordered lunch there which was also a little pricey for a salad but I was so relaxed I didn't care. There is a door to go outdoors to a coed pool and jacuzzi. There is also a fridge that you can have unlimited juices, water, and fruit.Restaurants: For breakfast, Ceres is best! They have a breakfast buffet that is really good! You can sit outside on the patio or you can eat indoors. Speidini's is really good too! It's an italian-type restaurant and is great for dinner. The hotel is connected to the Rampart Casino. I do not recommend eating at the Rampart Buffet for either breakfast, lunch, or dinner. I heard mixed reviews of that place, but after eating there, my husband and I both felt a little queezy. And we have iron stomachs! The Promenade cafe is good for lunch. There's a Starbucks there that comes in handy. The Carmel Room is a pretty good steakhouse. It's a la carte, so it can be a bit pricey. There are these secluded tables that are seperated by curtains for privacy. Pretty cool. If you eat there, just request one to the hostess. There's no extra charge for them. Checkout: Checkout was pretty easy. If you need a ride to the airport you can take their shuttle for $30 per person. The only bad thing is the shuttle only leaves at certain times and there are only 4 or 5 time slots. So you have to hope that your flight is somewhere around that. The other choice is a private vehicle for $50 that can pick you up whenever you want. Since there were me and my husband it was not only cheaper for us to take the private vehicle, but it was also more convenient (time-wise). The valet guys are really nice and very hospitable, so make sure you tip them. The only thing about the hotel is it's location. It's not on the strip and about a 15+ minute drive from the strip. It's in the Summerlin area which is on the other side of town. However, it is really nice and very relaxing. Since there's a casino attached, you can get your gamble fix in as well. There's also a casino next door and another one a few miles away.	
Nov 14 2009 	Not impressed	This hotel is billed as a nice resort in Vegas, but it's anything but. I was surprised to find that there is no option for wifi, at least in the palm tower. The rooms have ancient tube TVs, and the remote for my room did not function. There was also a stench of open sewer throughout the building the weekend of my stay. The free parking for the Palm tower is a long walk from the front door. Your other option is paying for a valet with tips.The rooms a a good size, and the restaurant area is pretty nice, but to be honest, the place feels deserted - almost too empty. It feels dead.	
Nov 5 2009 	Not the best Marriott experience I've had	This was a mixed bag, to be sure. The rooms are certainly large and nicely appointed. The view of the mountains from our room was spectacular. Though we didn't use the pool, it's lovely and huge. Did use the hot tub which could've been hotter but was warm and bubbly and after a long day walking on the strip was perfect. The grounds are beautiful and staff was invariably pleasant and helpful. So why wasn't I thrilled. Let's start in the bathroom. It's enormous with a jacuzzi tub and separate shower. But on getting into the shower, it appeared that there was black mildew growing where the &quot;seat&quot; built into the shower met the floor. Which was creepy. On closer inspection, there was simply no grout there at all, those were unfilled gaps I was seeing. Also kind of creepy. The lighting was another issue. While there were five lights in the bedroom/living area, with all of them turned on, it was still dim. But the bathroom was the worst. The lighting was behind a cove, and even with the lighted makeup mirror, it was difficult to see well enough to even put on makeup. The hairdryer was one of those small travel-type dryers with two settings - burning hot tornado or light breeze cool. It made it really difficult to use and I very much regretted not bringing my own dryer, though in general, we stay at Marriotts and they have much higher quality dryers. Another issue was transportation to the strip. I found either on the conference brochure or their web site (can't remember which) that there was a shuttle to the strip. I am SO glad I called because this shuttle, during the week, goes 3 times a day. So you can't come and go at your leisure and if you go in the morning, you are pretty much trapped there all day unless you're willing to spend $50 (I'm told) on a cab. This is definitely not a hotel I'd ever stay in without a rental car. The casino seems small and shabby. It didn't seem at all up to par with the strip hotels, and certainly not to the casino at the red rock resort which is only about 10-15 minute from the Marriott. We were there for a business meeting and so didn't have a choice on where to stay. I have to say though that I would never choose to stay at this hotel. Too many negatives and way too many other choices.	
Oct 14 2009 	Extremely Comfortable and Elegant...	As a former resident of Las Vegas (Summerlin specifically), I was pretty familiar with the JW Marriott and was excited to stay there as a tourist. I'd never been in the rooms before and opted to stay in a Jr. Suite. The size of the suite was ample, but at $309.00/night I couldn't help but be extremely critical of a few issues. The first being the TV. I thought at this caliber of hotel, all the TV's would be upgraded to flat screens with high definition picture quality but the TV in the suite was quite old and outdated. I've stayed in Holiday Inn's with better TVs. Second, there's a fee for internet access--I find this absolutely appalling when the rates are what they are. Third and most nit picky of all, the armoire was scratched and the couch was slightly stained and very faded. These are very easy fixes and I expect that from this hotel. What I loved about the hotel outweighed the bad. The bed was the best feature as it was extremely comfortable and well dressed. The bathroom was fabulous with a large jacuzzi tub and rainfall shower. I loved the walk in closet and the french doors. The ceiling fan was a nice touch. I ordered room service one night and was very pleased. And lastly, the courtyard/pool area is simply breathtaking. If I were to stay here again, I think I would choose a regular room as I didn't feel the living room furniture and setup were that great. Overall, I was comfortable and happy and just slightly disappointed.	
