Aug 31 2009 	Getting tired - needs updating	We have been staying at this property near Las Vegas for about 5 years. It's funny how new hotels pop up and suddenly your &quot;old&quot; hotel has lost its charm. That's definitely happening with the JW Marriott Las Vegas. The rooms and the common areas (hallways, dining room, even casino and bathrooms) are simply not in the same league as other 4 or 5 star properties in Las Vegas. The casino and establishments near it are also getting &quot;tired&quot;. Having stayed at several JW's over the past 5 years, this one simply continues to look more and more dated as the years go by. The furnishings and decor are all very dull and uninspired. They never really tried too hard to tie in the southwestern feel of Nevada nor did they try to make it particularly luxurious which would be fine if this were a regular Marriott property rather than a JW. We did appreciate that the parking is free although the valets were busy chatting when we were struggling to get our bags out the door the morning we checked out. Housekeeping also needs to be told to &quot;use their inside voices&quot; because one yelling down the hall to the other at 8am is simply unacceptable. The breakfast staff at the main restaurant &quot;Ceres&quot; were all very good to us but we did have an issue with one man at the front desk. Breakfast for 2 was included in our room but my husband did not have any &quot;coupons&quot; with him so the waiter simply suggested he go to the front desk to get coupons. The front desk clerk was very irritated that the waiter suggested this and my husband ended up walking all the way back to our 4th floor room (which was some distance) only to find they never provided any coupons. In May we stayed at the JW Desert Ridge in Phoenix and breakfast was also included. There, you simply advise your name and room number and they take care of the rest. Here at the LV location, it's apparently like the food hall at your old college campus. This is not the way most 4/5 star resorts operate and in a hotel like this, the front desk should have been more concerned about the guest rather than their displeasure with a coworker. We chose this hotel partly because of its proximity to Red Rock Canyon - where we like to hike - but also the fact that it's not on the strip and we wanted to relax on the first leg of our trip (we returned to Vegas and stayed at The Palazzo the following week). The other reasons we chose this hotel was because of the size of the rooms in the main building and the pool area - which I still love. I do however believe there were some people at the pool who were not guests at the resort which I never care to see and I wish hotels were more vigilant about that. I just hope that Marriott can take a real hard critical look at this property and bring it back up to JW standards. I would still recommend this hotel to a friend but only if I gave them the entire picture. While we truly enjoyed our time by the pool - even though it should stay open longer in the summer - this place needs to be freshened up.	
