Oct 25 2007 	Sketchy Service kind of a bummer	This is kind of a confusing hotel. Rooms are great and typical of an upper-end property, but the layout of the hotel is a bit bizarre. The previous review that said that the hotel wasn't for disabled travellers wasn't joking...I'd also add that it isn't the best for hoofing around in a pair of high heels either!I'd reckon that the endless corridors orginated when the Marriott planning team tried to work its way around the Rampart Casino. The hotel is pretty crisp in a reassuring, vanilla kind of way until you walk through the casino hub...then it's all worn carpet, low ceilings and cigarette smog. Not exactly ringing the five-star bell, if you know what I mean.All of that aside, however, I probably won't rank it as low if it wasn't for the dodgy service issues we encountered. Nothing earth-shattering, but the lot would put me off staying at the hotel again. Stuff that happened during our stay included...--Laundry that showed up at the last possible second. We had sent some suits in to be pressed when we arrived early the first afternoon and we were told they'd run it through and have it up the next morning. Late the following afternoon, as we were contemplating how to spruce up our t-shirts for a business dinner, we were told that the order had been sent off-property and it still wasn't back. The gal on the phone was very helpful and entertained our half-hourly nervous phone calls but it was a little too close for my taste.--Concierge apathy. We needed some information on how to get ahold of a few simple things and both gals suggested that we check the local shops. Funny that I didn't think of that. I was a concierge myself, and I dimly remember something about assisting the guests by providing specific information, and even calling a few places if I didn't know the information off the top of my head. Being as we didn't know the area, even a nudge in the right direction would have been helpful.--Strident telephone operators. My cell phone wasn't working, I was down on the Strip and I needed to contact my husband at the hotel. I had the room card jacket so I called the number on it. The operator patched me through to the room. As soon as I set the phone down, I realized that I needed one more piece of info so I called the hotel again. This time a different operator tells me that she can't connect me. I have to call the local number. I explain that I'm calling from a borrowed phone, and that I had just reached the room moments earlier. Besides, each piece of hotel information in my purse only lists two phone numbers for the hotel; a 877 phone number and a local fax.She tells me that she CAN NOT connect me. It is impossible. She will be happy, however, to give me the local number if I can find a pen. I said again that I was on a borrowed phone and could I please speak to a manager. She sent me to a voice mail box. When I got back to the room, I sifted through my purse again. I had the hotel brochure and a bunch of little cards from the room key jacket. All have the 877 phone number listed. I'm confused why this number is prevalent if guests aren't allowed to use it once they are in the hotel. Overall, there were just a bunch of little details like this that kept the stay from being relaxing and enjoyable. Could have just been our bad luck that we kept running into so many off-putting quirks, but I don't think that I would ever venture back to this hotel again when there are so many other premium options in the area.	
