Oct 9 2007	Beautiful location but.....	Everybody has his own criteria when he chooses a hotel. In my case, I pick out a hotel based on the expected view from the room. This is why I make it a rule to stay at Paris Hotel Premier Rooms as opposed to Bellagio Deluxe Lakeview Rooms when I stay on the strip (I personally believe that the fountain looks more beautiful and interesting when you see it from the street side, as opposed to from inside the the Bellagio building...). I was interested in staying at a hotel with a cool view of the Red Rock Mountain this time. Unfortunately, Red Rock Hotel seemed a bit expensive when I checked it on their website. So, I did some search and found out that there's this hotel called J.W. Marriott in Summerlin area.I was planning to rent a car (and see the outskirts of Vegas) anyway, and the distance from the strip was not a problem at all. I actually enjoyed the drive on the expressway going up north and west towards the beautiful mountains. The hotel property was very large, and I was impressed by the beautiful entrance with palm trees.I was a bit early (1PM) when I checked in. But I thought this might be better in terms of room choices. I booked what they called &quot;view room&quot; on their website. Though it says &quot;view&quot;, I was OCD enough to ask the woman at the front desk for &quot;a room with a great view&quot;. She was very helpful and told me I was lucky because there's a room available facing the mountain and the golf course available in the SPA Tower. I had no idea where the SPA Tower was located, but I thanked her and headed for the room. I had no complaint about the room per se. It was capacious and had all the necessary amenities. The bath room was marvelous. But when I walked to the window, supposedly to enjoy the view, I was stunned. There sure is a golf course beyond the hotel driveway. But I had to turn my head sharply to the right (west) to have a blocked and partial view of the Red Rock Mountain. Well, obviously, this SPA Tower is facing north and south. If you choose a regular room, you have an unremarkable view looking down the hotel garden. And if you choose the view room, it faces towards the south and you have to look to the right (west) to have a mountain view if any.I went back to the front desk and asked the same person if there is any room available in the other tower called Palm Tower. based on their map, this building is facing west and east, and if you're assigned a room facing west, you should be able to enjoy the beautiful view of Red Rock Mountain. She first apologized and the told me that the view rooms of the Palm Tower had been all booked up. Well, I told her that I had come in early enough and I must be the first person to check in on the day. I asked her how these rooms had been booked up already. She was quiet a little bit, almost looking like trying to find an excuse, and then started to explain that some conferences had been going on the whole week, bluh, bluh, bluh........I'm sure there must be a way to book the view room (facing west) of the Palm Tower, but it seems that as long as we book in an ordinary way (marriott.com, hotels.com.....etc), the &quot;view room&quot; by default means the room of SPA Tower facing south. Correct me, anyone, if I am wrong. Again, the room was nice, but as a view-sucker, I regretted not staying at the Red Rock Hotel. Period.	
Oct 8 2007 	OK nice location away from the Strip	We stayed in this hotel after a week on the Strip- what a blessing to see a bit of &quot;normal&quot; that Vegas had to offer! It was easy to find, 15mins from the Strip, within 2 mins drive to the nearest local restaurants and shops, big rooms, romantic gardens and lovely pool area.We booked using the Labor Day discount and found ourselves in a tired-looking room with 2 Queen beds (they didn't have any King beds left) with a view of the road, so maybe you get what you pay for? Plus the TV had poor reception, the AC wasn't easy to control and the extra room for the luggage was actually too small for the purpose. Saving grace was the bathroom with the wonderful rain-shower! Service I found to be a bit on the poor side- our luggage was dumped on the floor by a trainee porter who looked extremely hot and bothered and had his shirt buttons undone. The receptionist at the check in counter gave the impression of being very rushed although there were only a few people there. In comparison the Bellagio check-in counter was extremely slow but once you got there they treated you 100% better and catered to every need. The valets were polite and quick though..Pool smelled strongly of chlorine but it was exactly the same at the Bellagio.All in all, I rated this hotel an average coz it really was.. average. After a week of staying at the best hotels in Vegas I wasn't really impressed with the room or the service. For the price we paid we should have stayed longer at Signature (best hotel in Vegas!). I might stay here again if it was fully booked everywhere else.	
Oct 7 2007 	Good hotel if you want a little bit of peace and quiet away from the Strip	PROSLovely grounds and a little bit of peace away from the lights and sounds of the Strip. Rooms are well sized and there is good choice interms of food and entertainment on site. The themed Irish pub is a bit like being back in an O'Neills in London but with much better food and cheaper beer (even the Irish aleis cheaper!)The casino is small by Vegas standards but a good way to learn the ropes before losing even bigger sums in the resort hotels on the Strip.Buffet breakfast was included and was good quality with varied selection.Red Rock Canyon is only about a 20 minute drive away and well worth the trip. There is a well signed scenic drive which is great around sunset.CONSHotel wasn't very busy but we still found ourselves having to wait a little to get anyway from reception when wanting to use the business suite and had to wait to be seated (around 10 minutes) each morning for breakfast. We presume would be quite long during peak season.Not exactly a typical Vegas hotel and drive to the Strip is around 20 minutes with good traffic. The free shuttle service to the Strip is very useful but again, during peak season is must get a little fretful as it is first come first served and only goes every hour.(However you can park at all the main Strip hotels so driving there and back isn't a real problem unless you plan to drink)SUMMARYOverall a very nice hotel and we would stay here again but having stayed one night at The Hotel at the Mandalay Bay we would suggest that if you want the full Vegas experience you go for a hotel on the Strip.	
