Sep 12 2007 	Peace 	Husband and I stayed here last week for 1 night. We are not Vegas people by any means, and have dreaded previous visits to this city for business. I'm glad to know that such a comfortable resort is available and within 20 minutes of the airport. We had a Deluxe Guest Room with a balcony. Balcony was only 18 inches deep so obviously not furnished with seating. Not much of a purpose unless you're a smoker in need. The room was tastefully decorated and very clean. Bed was comfy with nice sheets and down comforters. The bathroom was stunning! Lots of marble and glass. Separate soaking whirlpool. Large glass shower that gives you the option of a &quot;rain shower&quot; or traditional shower head. Separate commode room. The rooms were very similar in quality and design to the rooms at any of the newer Ritz Carlton properties. I know that Marriott owns RC, perhaps they're sharing designers! If I can have the same accommodations as the RC at Marriott prices, count me in!The Marriott has its own casino. It's noisy and smoke-filled just like the real thing. In true Vegas form, you must walk through the casino to get to most areas of the resort including restaurants. We dined at Spiedini and it was acceptable. We didn't want to venture out onto the strip on a Fri. night in search of something more extraordinary. The breakfast at the Promenade Cafe was pretty standard diner fare. Our server was exceptional, though!If you find yourself in the unenviable position of being stranded in Las Vegas against your will, I would highly recommend the JW Marriott as it's about as far removed from the strip as one can get without renting a car. It's still Vegas, but at least the most of the crowds, noise and general smut is kept at bay.	
Sep 5 2007 	Glad we stayed here and not on the Strip!	My wife and I choose this destination for our second honeymoon. We wanted a location that offered good weather, great restaurants, and lots to do. Las Vegas fit the bill nicely. We researched the hotels and felt that the JW would be our best choice. We are confident we made the right choice. If you see some negative reviews of the JW, posted here, they are almost certainly written by people who did not do their homework. If you are looking for round-the-clock, hot-time, Las Vegas excitment; stay on the Strip. That is NOT what you stay at the JW for! We wanted our hotel to be away from all of the noise, congestion, and mobs that you find at the mega-hotels on the Strip. The JW proved to be a beautiful, clean, and serene place to unwind and releax. We visited the Strip three times during our five day stay in Vegas; and it was great being able to escape the madness when we were through with the Strip for the day. In looking at the other reviews posted here, I would have to say that I agree with the overall opinions on the JW's restaurants and food. Basically, not bad, not spectacular. The on-site restaurant, Ceres, did a respectable job with the breakfast buffet. We had our last night's dinner in the JW's Italian-themed restaurant, Spiedini. It was a little underwhelming when compared to some of the the dinners we had outside the JW, but no serious complaints. FYI, if you stay at the JW, be sure to have a &quot;special occasion&quot; dinner at Rosemary's Restaurant, which is nearby. It is the highest Zagat-rated restaurant in the Las Vegas area, and was featured by Rachel Ray on one of the Travel Channel programs, but definitely not &quot;$40 a day&quot;!Our room, a Junior Suite, was large, beautiful and always kept clean by the staff. The bed was very comfortable, with high quality sheets. My only complaint was that it was difficult to get a consistent, comfortable temperature in the room (I like it chilly for sleeping).The staff was always courteous and helpful. The Spa was terrific. The Casino seems geared to the casual gamer. There are a lot of video poker and slot machines that are penny and nickel types. And most of the black jack tables are five or ten dollar minimums (on the weekday anyway).All in all, I highly recommend the JW and would gladly return.	
Sep 4 2007	Peace and Quiet	The hotel is huge. The place is very very clean. I have a bedroom with the double French door with the view of the mountain. The location of the hotel is near restaurants, gas station, and other convenience stores. The hotel is 10 minutes driving distance away from the LV Strip. The mattress and bed linen are so comfortable. It makes me wanted to buy the same mattress that the hotel is using. The bathroom is so big that it has a whirlpool bath, separate shower, separate toilet room, and a double sink. The toiletry is excellent. The free form swimming pool is very big and it has few swimming laps that are 25 meters long. The hotel appearance is well kept. The garden is pleasant to walk through. There are many lounge chairs by the pool. The hotel provides free valet parking. The buffet lunch in the hotel was about $ 9.00, good food and good price. Other time, I ate out. Do not go to the Las Vegas Chinatown, the food is terrible and expensive comparing to New York, Los Angeles, or Toronto. The LV Strip is crowded with people. The exhaust from the cars and hotels air conditioner make the place extremely hot. I go into the hotels to cool off. The hotels architectural structures and its interior are nice, I took many photographs of Bellagio, Caesar Palace, and Venetian.	
