Sep 2 2007 	Lovely comfortable hotel away from the glitz	It is a pleasure to stay at the JW Marriott Las Vegas Resort. It is an oasis of calm and taste in the nice suburb of Summerlin, yet provides a free shuttle service to the Fashion Show Mall on the Strip when you feel like a little more excitement.The service is efficient, friendly and helpful: they provided a refrigerator for our room at no extra charge (my partner is diabetic and needs to keep his insulin chilled) and a faulty lightbulb in the walk-in wardrobe was changed immediately. The chamber maids are excellent and even let us use their vacuum cleaner to suck the air out of the vacuum bags we used to carry some king sized pillows home to the UK.Our spa-tower bedroom for our four night stay was lovely and large with a balcony, luxurious bathroom and walk-in wardrobe.The selection of restaurants was OK, but not wonderful and they close early in the evening - the choice is very limited unless you eat before 9pm. The Cafe was about the best but, as usual in the USA, the helpings are very large and really need to be shared by two. We ate in the Irish pub on our last night and the food there was quite good. There is a small Starbucks, which is a very good idea, but their croissants and pastries are an utter disappointment for a European when compared with French ones.The pool was disappointing. It is too shallow to swim properly and the poolside cafe was not well stocked and closed early. Apparently there are very few pools deeper than 3 or 4 feet in Las Vegas - except in older hotels - due to insurance company restrictions, which seems silly, since people can drown in a few inches of water in some circumstances. It takes the pleasure out of swimming. Despite large signs everywhere with pool rules prominently saying no diving, at least six people did so during my 45 minute swim one late afternoon - the lifeguard was looking the other way every time, though he must have heard the splashes. The pool did not have a good atmosphere and was a longish walk from the hotel. The cabanas were very basic. The waterfall was nice, though.The shopping centre nearby was huge and comprehensive and had many stores that weren't found on the Strip, including a good supermarket. However, the shuttle bus to the Fashion Show Mall on the Strip was very quick and convenient and the driver even handed out free bottles of chilled water, which was essential in the August heat.Summerlin is a lovely area and the hotel was relaxed and pleasant. It is not as exciting or vibrant as staying on the Strip, but fun nevertheless.	
Aug 28 2007 	Wonderful stay after initial disappointment - handled well by management	My family and I chose the JW Marriott to begin and end a tour of the national parks. We arrived on a Sunday afternoon, in 115 degree heat, eager to use the pool following our five hour flight. We were notified that the pool was closed for cleaning for the rest of the day due to child pollution and we were sent to the pool at the Suncoast, about  a mile away. We were assured our pool would be open the next day.I had researched pools in Las Vegas and finding an awesome pool was the priority for our short time in Vegas. The JW Marriott pool seemed to fit the bill in every way.except that it wasnt open.The next morning, we were ready for a swim before our drive to the Grand Canyon....only to find out the pool was still closed. Apparently they close it for 24 hours, and there is only one main pool.After (respectfully) voicing my complaints and preparing to cancel our reservation for our return stay, the manager, very graciously, deducted part of our bill and upgraded us to a suite for our return stay, throwing in a couple passes to the spa for my husband and me. I have to say, you can tell a lot about a place with how they handle problems and we left as satisfied guests.Upon our return to JW, the pool was very clean and beautiful, and it did not disappoint. Because there are so many palm trees, there were plenty of chairs with shade. I couldnt help noticing a toddler swimming without rubber swim pants.I looked at the pool rule sign and it says &quot;no soiling&quot;, however, it does not specify that babies and toddlers should be required to wear rubber swim pants. This kind of problem really is preventable and the resort should make this a requirement to avoid other disappointments.We had a few meals at the JW: breakfast at Ceres, lunch at the Waterside Cafe and a lunch at JC Wooloughan, the Irish pub. All meals were very good. My husband and I loved the spa pool, and our suite was beautiful, with a great view and double balcony. Our rooms on both stays were spotless.It took us an hour to get to the Strip as there was traffic (an accident on one trip), and we must have gotten off at the wrong exit since we were stuck in Strip traffic for awhile. We went to the Red Rock Resort for dinner and bowling on our second night. The teenagersliked the bowling.The rooms and the complex are beautiful and well landscaped. Despite our initial disappointment, we had a fantastic stay on our return trip. The manager did an excellent job addressing our concerns.	
Aug 24 2007 	Nice Change of Pace	I stayed for three nights in late June. As a native of Las Vegas, I don't need the neon hassles of the Strip. My preference is a well maintained hotel with great service. I especially appreciated NOT having to walk through a wall of cigarette smoke to get to my room. The grounds are beautiful and well maintained, the rooms are clean, modern and in good repair (I was amazed at the &quot;worn&quot; comment). The bathrooms are luxurious, the beds comfortable, the couch and chairs worthy of sinking into for a good chat with friends of a late evening. Finally - the staff. Stellar. From the moment I arrived tired, hot and ready to collapse (delayed flights, car rental mix-ups, and a late evening drive through the awful Las Vegas traffic) it was just wonderful. The valet were helpful and courteous, the front desk staff cheerful and professional. The cleaning staff always gave a cheerful &quot;good morning&quot; as I left, and I was greeted by the desk staff when I returned. A minor hiccup upon leaving was quickly and professionally resolved. I was so satisfied I even sent a compliment to Marriott directly. To those who say only &quot;over-50&quot; would stay there, surprise - I'm not and will not only stay there again but will highly recommend it for anyone looking for a great oasis of calm and refinement in Las Vegas. Sure, if all you want is pink neon, this is not your place.	
