Jul 31 2007 	Make sure to get a room with a balcony	I originally made the reservation with the hotel and was told we would get a room with a balcony. When we arrived I was told that those rooms were sold out way in advance. Although disappointed we were shown to an alternate room and were told to check with the concierge later in the week for availability. It wasn't until we had unpacked and went downstairs to scope out the property that we ran into the concierge for our tower. I told her to keep us in mind for a balcony room. She immediately checked out the availability in our tower and gave us the keys to a balcony room. Happily, we switched rooms out. If you care about not feeling claustrophobic then request a room with a balcony. Our room was small for the rate we paid. We usually stay at the Venetian for the same rate. But I must say the bed is the best bed I have ever slept on. The room had the usual amenities, great walk in closet, nice size jacuzzi tub and the waterfall shower head. We never had a problem with the hot water running out and it was nice to go into a hot jacuzzi after spending time playing tennis all day. Now for the balcony...It's nice to relax on the balcony as long as you don't have any neighbors doing the same thing on either side of you. In a five night stay we only ran into our neighbors twice. As far as the breakfast is concerned, we booked a rate which included breakfast for two in the cafe. The view from the restaurant outside was gorgeous. It was nice to look at the ponds and waterfalls. The best thing at the cafe are the belgian waffles. They melt in your mouth and you can't help but eat more than one serving. There's a great omelette bar, fruit, and your usual baked goodies. The only thing that kind of bothered us was when you went to the omelette bar a separate tip jar sat on the counter. Without our breakfast vouchers, breakfast would of easily been at least $30. Being pressured into tipping even more so early in the morning for someone to make your omelettes was annoying.Now if you don't get a room with breakfast, the Starbucks inside the casino has good pastries. I found out that the hotel makes them fresh for Starbucks. It's also open 24 hours in case you have the munchies.I think the best part of the hotel is not the outdor pool but the Gym/Spa. It's worth the $25 bucks to work out in it every day. Equipped with your above average machines you won't have to wait for a cardio machine or fight over free weights. It's beautiful, spacious yet private. The women's lockerroom/spa area is clothing optional so when you walk to use the sauna, steam room and jacuzzi, there's a state of undress which I would prefer to reserve for the privacy of my own home. In addition, they give you flip flops, a robe and a locker key for your $25 so you can use the facilities after working out. If you forgot a hairdryer, hair brush, lotion, shampoo they got it all, including a nice water and fruit bar for your convenience.The grounds are lovely and very green. You certainly don't feel like your in Las Vegas. It was our first time to stay away from the Strip and I think it's a nice hotel if you have a family and want to stay away from the hustle and bustle. As far as variety of restaurants they weren't lacking. A short drive to the nearby SunCoast and strip malls offer your usual chain varieties...PF Chang's, etc..By the way, we ate at the pool since it was recommended by one of the reviews. We had a lame burger, a tuna tartare salad and two drinks. It was a $40 waste of time. You're better off hopping into the car and finding something else. All in all it was a nice hotel but for the same hotel rate I'd prefer a suite at the Ritz or the Four Seasons.	
