Jun 12 2007 	Great resort	First, the drive there was terrible with construction on I-95, but that's not the hotel's fault. The service from valet to front desk was great. Overall service was among the best I have seen, with a verification phone call from the desk after all requests you make to ensure they were carried out. We stayed in the one bedroom suite. It was very large, especially the bedroom. It had a marble entrance and bathroom, inlaid with a design. The large shower had a rainfall head. The whole place felt like a nice Manhattan apartment. Only drawback was no flatscreen TVs, which are becoming standard in a Vegas hotel. The grounds were awesome, with walkways through trees, ducks, ponds, and streams (man-made). The pool was huge and never crowded. Go to the Mandalay pool and see what a crowd is like. Another drawback here was big winds blew a lot of debris in the pool, but the two lifeguards were having more fun hanging out and acting cool than working. &quot;The pool cleaner doesn't come back until tomorrow.&quot; was what they told me. &quot;Get me a net and I'll do it,&quot; I said, and I got a confused look from the two teens. Food was good, with several restaurants carrying the new expensive Vegas food prices. One restaurant overlooked the casino, but it was wide open with no glass and unless you asked to sit in the corners, you got the nasty cig smoke along with your meal. Overall, I would return again if I wanted to feel like I was off the strip, which you definitely felt here. On the strip, I would go to the Wynn or Signature at MGM for a nicer on-strip experience.	
Jun 8 2007 	Solid and Impressive but not a "Vegas" Hotel/Resort	I just returned from the JW Marriott Las Vegas, having spent four nights for a company meeting. This place has a lot to offer. They definitely have their act together when it comes to service. Long business meetings can be stressful and this hotel's staff made the experience much better. The resort is lush. First, it's beautiful and the grounds/pool are equally impressive. No problems on aesthetics . . . . rooms are up to date with marble foyer, patterned sisal carpet, pretty furnishings, etc. The bedroom area is outfitted with something comparable to a &quot;heavenly bed&quot; -very cloud like - - layered fresh, white sheets/duvet and the most comfortable collection of starched, clean pillows. This hotel feels a little like a Ritz. The marble bathroom has a wow factor. . . entirely marble (walls, floor, etc) w/ a soothing &quot;rain shower&quot; in a separate enclosure with bench, etc. giant jacuzzi tub in the corner that sits below mirrored walls - granite countertops -- luxurious. The Room Service was smooth and seamless and reasonably priced. I enjoyed breakfast three mornings and dinner one evening. In the interest of space, I won't describe every crouton, but suffice to say, you get precisely what you order and it's timely. It bears mentioning that the room service dinner I had was as good as some of the meals I've eaten at restaurants in Wynn ! - JW Mar. offers a Pan Roasted Halibut dinner w/ braised leeks and fingerling potatoes w/ a watercress, lemon sauce - - outstanding - - dessert was sinfully delicious (apple tart - baked just before it arrived) - mixed greens salad was large and fresh with thin slices of green apple and apple cider viniagrette. Three olive rolls and one whole wheat roll was on the cart w/butter. I was in heaven. One morning, I threw a curve to the guy taking the phone orders for breakfast, asking for a few substitutions. I was skeptical that it would arrive with the correct changes. It did. Nice! The lady who takes the room service orders needs to familiarize herself with the menu. My only complaint is that she was totally unaware of the specials they offer with regard to a free half bottle of wine when you order a three course dinner. She didn't know what the &quot;Good Start&quot; breakfast included - - a little annoying. One evening ( stayed on 5th floor) Vegas had high winds and it sounded like the french doors in my room were going to bust open. Imagine the way a tea pot sounds when it's &quot;going off&quot; only much more angry. I called the front desk and within minutes an engineer arrived and he stayed for over twenty minutes, attaching additional weather stripping until the doors were silent. I'm not going to &quot;ding&quot; the hotel for this because I valued the prompt response and attention that was offered to me. These folks are masters of service and it shows. Everyone had a smile and was eager to help in any way they could. I forgot my toothbrush and within a few minutes one was delivered to me with a sample of toothpaste. There's a 24 hour Starbucks near the Casino. What's nice about this hotel is that it's a hotel/resort with a casino - not the other way around. I find that most places in Vegas are smoke filled casinos with hotels attached. Now, as for my PITA (Pain in the [--] ) Factor: The tub was gorgeous but I didn't have time to use it and I'm glad because there were two stray, &quot;ahem&quot; pubic or some type of hairs on the side. I didn't call housekeeping, but I bet that if I did, they would have immediately sent someone to clean it. Also, the one drinking glass in my bathroom had a residue in the bottom (let's hope it was soap) - the other glasses were clean as a whistle. The worst, however, was the smell in the corridor of our meeting rooms. We spent four days in the Conference Center and certain areas had a sewage smell. Not all of our meeting areas were plagued with this odor, but it was very strong where they had our snack/break tables set up. It was bad. Back to the room:The toiletries are high end and displayed in a nice little wooden crate w/ wash cloths - - - Overall, this is a really nice place - I'd definitely stay there again. Still, it's not a &quot;Vegas&quot; hotel - it's a good twenty minute drive from the Strip. For that reason, I'd probably stay somewhere else on a personal trip to Vegas. For business, this place is upscale and delivers. Tasteful, elegant, solid.	
