May 29 2007 	Fantastic Room - Beautiful Grounds - Very Nice Area	We just returned from a 2 night getaway to Las Vegas and loved the JW Marriott! It is a beautiful hotel with gorgeous grounds and lovely views of the surrounding mountains. We have been to Las Vegas twice before and enjoyed Mandalay Bay but this was a more relaxing hotel. No walking a mile just to get to the pool here. The pool was a nice size and not too crowded - arrive early to get a chair near the pool. The waterfall was not working the weekend I was there. They had 2 guys and a steel drum performing on the weekend - nice atmosphere when you are on a vacation. We would not hesitate to bring our children here next time. The rooms are some of the largest I've seen. We had a regular room in the Palms Tower and it was huge. Our friends were next door in a suite that had a very large balcony and a very spacious living room as well as a large bedroom. Definately worth the extra money if you would like a place to meet up with friends/family before hitting the strip. The 1 bedroom had a small fridge and a wet bar. We had a view of the grounds and could see the strip as well. We rented a car and drove to the strip - about 20 minutes - parking at the strip resorts was easy and the way to go. No walking our feet off on this trip. We would highly recommend this type of Vegas experience if you don't have to be in the middle of all the action the whole time.	
May 28 2007 	Great room but eat elsewhere	Our family (2 adults and 2 children under 7) were in Vegas for a wedding and we stayed at the Summerlin JW Marriott due to its proximity to reception venue. The rooms were great for the price of $289 for the Jr. Suites. As described the other posts the rooms were well apponted with the exception of the TVs. Housekeeping and engineering were extremely responsive. A fact that is a big deal when you are traveling with kids. I would not recomend eating on the property at all. The service is surly at best if you happen to be unlucky enough to actually interact with a food and beverage emlpoyee. And once the food eventually arrives you are treated to a very poor dinng experience. The pool is a let down after you see the pictures on the website, the water fall was not operational. Similar to the F &amp; B people the pool staff seem to be more interested in catching up on their social life than actually working the crowd. Summary: great value on the rooms, great house keeping, engineering and valet staff. A good value for a very nice and quiet stay off of the Strip. Just drive down Rampart or go to the Strip to eat.	
May 28 2007 	Wonderful stay at the JW Marriott! Relaxing mellow resort.	My husband and I stayed here for 3 days after spending a couple of days at the Venetian, on the Strip. It was our 5th wedding anniversary and we could not have hoped for a nicer resort than the JW! It was very relaxing, especially after spending a couple of hectic days at the Strip. We are in our mid/late 20's. I consider myself a budget traveler, always looking for good deals, coupons, etc. - so this review is written in light of that. Using a special rate, we booked the JW Marriott for only $100/night. It was worth every penny.The grounds of the JW are beautiful &amp; clean - with very lush landscaping. The pool is large with plenty of lounge chairs. We never had a problem getting chairs and we visited over Memorial Day weekend. There were limited shady places though. The pool was quite crowded at times, with young folks partying it up and lots of kids splashing around (we don't mind either, but I could see how the pool might have been too loud for some people). It seemed like there were several weddings taking place over the weekend and the wedding parties were having a lot of fun socializing &amp; drinking at the pool. There is bar/grill right next to the pool where you can buy drinks/BBQ/burgers. The hotel has several restaurants and a 24 hr Starbucks. There were limited options for dining at breakfast and lunch - however, everything was open at dinner. The room was super-clean, and the bathroom was awesome. Marble tile, whirlpool tub, separate toilet area. The room wasn't overly-decorated or too extravagant but we found this calming, after staying at the Venetian immediately prior. Our room was on the 5th floor of the Palms Tower and looked out towards the east. We could see the city lights and the strip in the distance. It had a VERY small balconey (6 inches deep?). I noticed lower rooms had larger balconeys and rooms on the bottom floor had little patios with tables &amp; chairs. We did not visit the spa but it did look really nice. A spa treatment includes entry to a deluxe fitness center - however, there is a small free fitness room on the 2nd floor of the Palms Tower. I checked the spa brochure, and to me - the prices for treatments seemed high. But I can be pretty cheap ;-) Facials were more than $150 just to give you an idea. As far as transportation goes - there is an airport shuttle which costs $25/per person. A cab ride back to the airport costs about $45 I believe. However, the resort has a free shuttle to the Fashion Show Mall on the strip. We hopped on that with our luggage when we left, and thus - only had to pay cab fare from the Strip to the airport ($15).The casino is small - and not too fancy. Smoky, as can be expected. We played a little here and got a comped buffet meal for Sunday brunch. The brunch was so - so. Husband enjoyed the all-you-can eat crab legs and shrimp. The only other not-perfect thing about this resort, was that some of the hallways were somewhat sparse &amp; barren. As though they were waiting for some new restaurants or shops to go in. We only stayed 3 days, but I think we might have become a little tired of the dining options available if we had stayed much longer. Also, there is not too much going on here after about 8pm, except for the casino. It is a quiet, laid-back resort and the pool closes at 7pm. No live music or anything of the sort at night while we were there. As mentioned above, we are budget travelers and got a great rate at the JW. The JW Marriott is one of the nicest places we have stayed. In general, the other guests were much older than us and showed signs of being extremely wealthy (ie, valet parking Bentleys &amp; Rolls, carrying designer handbags, blah blah blah). The casino and buffets appear to be popular with the local senior citizen crowd. The pool is awesome and the kiddies seemed to be loving it. We didn't notice any &quot;weirdos&quot; here, like there were at the Venetian. Overall, I would recommend this place to people with kids and to older couples. Or to anyone looking for a very quiet and mellow resort experience. ;-)	
May 20 2007 	Beautiful Hotel (VERY QUIET)	Just got back. Very beautiful hotel and lovely pool with plenty of lounge chairs. Too bad the waterfall was not working. Apparently it has been broken for sometime now. Old 50's music is played by the pool. I grew up with that stuff and I am tired of hearing it. Wanted to hear some recent music, we are in Vegas! The hotel was very clean and neat with beautiful views of Red Rock. The bathroom was spacious with separate toilet room, whirlpool tub and a shower with a rainhead and a regular shower nozzel. Not much water pressure. Double sinks and extras. The refrigerator is a large cooler, it states that is not a refrigerator but a cooler, OK. The bed was comfortable with very soft sheets. Small TV that did not work well. The iron was broken and a new one was brought up quickly with friendly service. The cafe next to the casino inside was cheap and good. There is also a Starbucks located in the hotel next to the casino. The restaurant/cafe inside the hotel was expensive. The casino was sparse with people and the people that were in there were probably not a day younger than 60 and had walkers, oxygen tanks and lots of cigerettes. This is NOT your hotel if you are looking for action. Go to the strip. This hotel is VERY QUIET except for maybe the pool where the kids suddenly come out of the woodwork. You also have to pay for in-room internet access, $10.00 for 24hrs. Most hotels have free wireless. If you want to go to the strip and you have no car they have a shuttle service with a $25 per person fee. If you just want rest, relaxation, peace and quiet with some gambling and golf this is the place for you.	
