Oct 20 2006 	Beautiful Las Vegas Resort without the Strip Congestion	October 15 to 17, 2006  I had the opportunity to spend two nights at the JW Marriott Las Vegas Resort at Summerlin to attend a business meeting.I arrived about noon, hours before normal check-in, and was able to receive a room in about thirty minutes. The first room I had was #1518. From what I could tell it was a standard guest room on the 3rd floor of the Spa Tower. The room was quite large and had an outstanding bathroom. Until October 1st it had been a smoking room and there was a slight smell of smoke which bothered me.I went back to the front desk and the after the associate apologized and made a note for housekeeping she offered me an upgraded room; a parlor suite on the first floor #1115. It was smoke free and an awesome room!Besides being happy receiving an upgraded room, I was even more pleased at how my complaint was handled. There was no hesitation to offer an apology and correct the problem immediately. About ten minutes after I checked into my replacement room the front desk associate called to make sure that I was completely satisfied; great service!Getting to see both a standard room and a parlor suite was nice. Both of the rooms had huge and beautiful bathrooms. Both had whirlpool tubs large enough for two and both had huge showers with regular and rainfall shower heads.Neither room had a proper desk or office-style chair. Both offered wired high-speed internet service for $9.95 for 24 hours. The service worked well and connected with our corporate VPN, but did not work as smoothly as I-Bahn (STSN) which most Marriott properties offer. A minor annoyance was that electrical outlets were hidden and hard to get to. The rooms seem better designed for the leisure traveler instead of a business traveler.Both rooms were immaculate and during my short stay housekeeping was excellent. The bath amenities were generous sized and of very good quality. The bath linens were plentiful, fresh and thick. There were two thick resort robes in the walk-in closets which both rooms had. There was an electronic-locking safe in the closets as well as iron, ironing board, and a bottle of water to refill the steam iron!Room 1518 had a window but no balcony. Suite 1115, on the ground floor, had a huge patio. It made me feel like having a party! Both rooms offered large TVs with a large variety of cable channels and pay-per-view movies. The Murphy-style bed in my parlor suite was very comfortable; more comfortable than my bed at home!The resort has two towers, the Spa Tower, where my room was, and the Palms Tower. The two are connected by long concourses which connect through the Rampart Casino. The Aquae Sulis full service Spa at the resort and resort shop are located on the Spa Tower concourse. A food court located on the Palms Tower concourse and is home to: Starbucks, the Rampart Buffet, Shizen (Japanese) and several other restaurants.To get to the conference center requires either going outdoors or going through the casino. While the hotel is now 100% smoke free, the casino and the food court are not. The casino seemed fairly large and had lots of slots and all the table games for those interested in gambling.The hotel has a very small exercise room located on the 2nd floor of the Palms Tower that is complimentary. A much larger and much better equipped exercise area is located within the Aquae Sulis Spa, but there is a charge of $25.00 per day to use it and the other spa facilities.I walked through the pool area after meetings one day. The pool is huge and looked very inviting. There appeared to be plenty of lounges and pool towels. There are a number of cabanas around the pool each with a TV, table and chairs, and lounges. On the Palms Tower end is both a large waterfall and an outdoor hydrotherapy pool. Food and drink are available at the pool from the Waterside Caf. Behind the pool caf is a sand volleyball court, horseshoe pit, bocce ball area and croquet lawn. Besides all this, the hotel sits between two golf courses.All of my meals were in conjunction with the meeting that I was attending so I did not have the opportunity to try any of the hotels restaurants or room service except for Starbucks.I can recommend the JW Marriott for those who want to be in Vegas, but not be in the congestion of the Strip. Service was excellent and the accommodations were very good.	
Oct 16 2006 	Great stay.	I am a 37 year old male who took his mother, brother and sister-in-law to visit Las Vegas, the Grand Canyon, and Red Rock Canyon. We stayed at the J.W. Marriott from October 4 through the 9th. I have high standards for comfort and service and have stayed at similar resorts before all over the world. Paid for 2 junior suites (about 900 sq. ft. each) at $309 (plus fees and taxes) each per day.Pool: excellent. Excellent service/food, excellent size of pool and pool area, excellent background music, excellent landscaping. Lots of thyme has been planted throughout the beautifully landscaped property and you catch the faint fragrance when you're lying by the pool. Anecdote: I came to the pool bar to order food 5 minutes before closing and the chef was in the process of closing down his station. I asked if I could still order and he said: &quot;no problem&quot; and whipped us up a great BBQ chicken sandwich and cashew chicken eggrolls. Great service!Cerres: the resort restaurant. Excellent breakfasts (didn't try their lunch or dinners). Worth the $14 per person (plus tip) to start the day of right. Fresh and ripe fruits, delicious mozzarella/tomato salad, various cheeses/breads, freshly made omelets and scrambled eggs among other, heavier breakfast items such as potato and sausage. Great view of lush landscaping and waterfalls outside through 14 foot floor to ceiling windows. Overall wonderful service by people who obviously enjoyed serving guests. Anecdote: I came down one morning for breakfast with my party of 4 and was accosted by one of the breakfast floor managers (who will remain unnamed but is now known to the hotel manager after I wrote him about the incident) who stated, in front of my entire party, that I hadn't paid for my party the previous morning. I had indeed paid, including my usual 20% tip for any service I received at the resort. After checking with another floor manager she found out she was wrong but didn't have the decency to come tell me. I had to ask. I hope it happened because she had a bad day because she has no business being in the service industry if this is her normal behavior. Putting aside this weird incident, I can highly recommend eating breakfast at Cerres.Rooms: spacious, clean, cleaned fast and in an unobtrusive manner (you leave for just a moment and when you come back it's all done). I made small requests of the housekeeping staff once in a while (more bottled water, more hangers) and was always promptly satisfied. Spacious bathrooms, great features such a whirlpool bath, rain shower head, natural stone tiles, french doors that open (no balcony) to let fresh air in and give great views of Red Rock mountains on one side and downtown Vegas on the other. Excellent all.Hotel: is beautiful. Inside and out. Nothing spectacular (aside from the enormous and ubiquitous palm trees, I guess), just done right and very calming. Valet service was efficient. Best way to get to (and from) the Vegas strip is by taking Sahara if you want to end up at the North end of the strip and taking Tropicana if you want to end up at the South end of the strip. Don't take any other road as I must have tried them all to find the best ones. Either takes 30 minutes, less if all the lights are in your favor.Must see: &quot;O&quot; by Cirque de Soleil. Some people in the audience were actually so overcome with emotion they were weeping. Worth the $150 ticket. Don't get &quot;wet seat tickets&quot; if you are wearing something that you can't afford to get wet. Try the #1 rated Bellagio buffet before the show or the Olives restaurant. Take in the Bellagio fountains (every 15 minutes after dark) after the show. Grand Canyon by helicopter. We used Maverick Helicopter Tours and can't say enough good things about that outfit. Their modern office is conveniently located on the Vegas strip. Their helicopters are comfortable. Despite the rough weather conditions while getting to the Grand Canyon, the pilot was calm, cool and collected and a genuinely nice guy who gave just the right amount of commentary. There is no flying low for miles through the canyon which I guess I had anticipated from watching shows on television. Instead the pilot landed us on a cliff edge which gave us a great view of the majestic Grand Canyon and the river running through it. Great photo opportunities. Legends in Concert. I thought this would be cheesy but wanted to see it anyway. Glad I did because it was a great time. Live music, the impersonators' real voices, spot on impersonations of Britney Spears, Sting, Elvis, Garth Brooks, Four Tops (rocked the house!) and Bobby Darrin. Enthusiastic showgirls made it complete. The Forum Shops at Ceasar's Palace. Fantastic shops (hundreds of them) in a classy environment. Convenient valet parking in front. Fancy and casual restaurants througout. Simply the best shopping area on the Strip. Red Rock Canyon which is located just 15 minutes from the resort going West on Charleston Avenue. Beautiful vistas and great hiking/biking trials. When I return, I'll probably give the Bellagio or the Wynn hotel a try but I have a feeling I'll regret not staying at the J.W. Marriott again.	
