Feb 15 2006	Leaving Las Vegas	My wife and I recently returned from this hotel, questioning our opinion of the Marriott brand. In the plus side: staff were very friendly and helpful, food was good,price was good for LV ($233/night)for a large room. Problems were primarily maintenance related: floor (carpet) in room was filthy (cellophane wrapper, corn chip crumbs, fake eyelash, general dirt). Asked three times to have it vacuumed and when it was finally done, done very haphazardly and incomplete. One of the bathroom sink stoppers was broken and never fixed. The refrig in the room is actually only a cooler and you must add ice to keep things cool. Very poor for a 4 star hotel. We would give it another chance if the price was good, but were sadly disappointed with the service.	
Jan 2 2006	Beautiful and cosy..	I have traveled to more than 200 cities all over the world. As I remember, this resort has the best bathroom I have ever had. I do not know why it is rated 4 star hotel at all. Simply deserves 5 star and more! I had high expectations as I read all reviews on this hotel and my expectation was happily met. I stayed four different hotels in Vegas: JW Marriot resort, TI, Luxor, and Aladdin. so I might be able to give an unbiased review.1. Bathroom: Jacuzzi for two. huge. clean. 2. Bed: Very nice bed for those who love soft bed. I prefer Heavenly bed in Westin though. (I even ordered the bed from Westin for my own place.) But still nothing to be desired. a lot better bedding than normal 4 or 5 star hotel bed. 3. view: very nice mountain view. 4. Food: every restaurant is cheaper than those in Strip. for example, $9 here for breakfast vs. $13 in Strip. 5. Service: no complaint. front desk staffs were professional although I wish they would be more genuinely friendly like those in Aladdin.6. Casino: I am not a big gambler - that is why I stayed at the hotel. But the dealers at the Casino kindly taught me how to play. I really appreciate their kindness. very nice to talk to. 7. Transportation: $35 by Taxi. complimentary shuttle. last one from Strip is 11:30 pm which is way too early. The hotel needs to extend the shuttle time. Overall, I would love to stay if I visit Vegas with my boyfriend. Lovely bed and bathroom. Once I learned how to gamble, I probably will stay on Strip if I go myself. I already plan another trip to Vegas in Jan and made a reservation at Venetian this time.	
Jan 1 2006	Had Greater Expectations	Even though we had multiple communications with the hotel property prior to arrival, problems existed at check-in. We were given rooms above the parking lot, and after some aggressive discussion we tried another location. We eventually were given rooms consistent with what we had expected, except that the rooms were connected by a storage room in which plumbing pipes sounded off all night. The front desk did offer us a suite, but could not supply three proper beds, which we had reserved and requested, so we put up with the plumbing noises, which the desk staff refused to admit, while the maintenace people confirmed the consistent problem. The property is spacious and beautiful, but we were not told in advance that the pool area was closed, as well as the adjoning restaurants and bars, and parts of the outside were undergoing construction. Perhaps at another time of the year when the hotel is fully booked, this property will live up to the expectations expressed by other travelers. Even if you speak up, there is an intrinsic resistance for the staff to understand, let alone acquiese to reasonable requests. The restaurants are adequate, but the service is spotty, since most of the restaurants are independently operated at the adjoining casino. We also suspect that this property has a bias against hotel room consolidators and online travel agencies.	
Dec 28 2005	Excellent for a relaxing trip to Las Vegas	My husband and I stayed 4 nights, based on other trip advisor reviews. We loved the resort! Everyone was friendly, the room was perfect &amp; quiet, and the food was excellent. We stayed on a high floor in the palm tower, expecting a beautiful view - the mountains were pretty, but the closest view was of the roof of the other buildings. Room service breakfast was fabulous but we didn't get our free paper every morning. We enjoyed breakfast and lunch in the restaurant - they brought me a free dessert when they learned it was my birthday. All the waitstaff were very friendly. This hotel is inconvenient to the Strip, so not the place to stay if you want to spend most of your time in Vegas, but it's perfect if you just want to 'visit' Vegas. We took the shuttle in every evening (which only picks up every 2 hours and stops at 11:30 pm - way too early in my opinion). The taxis back to the hotel cost about $35 with tip. The hotel casino is small but sufficient for a few hours - the dealers weren't as professional and made a couple payout mistakes, but had no problem correcting them.	
Dec 27 2005	Perfect Getaway	The JW Marriott exceeded our expectations! The room was very big, ultra-clean and nicely decorated. The bathrooms are huge, with a wonderful rainfall showerhead and seperate jacuzzi tub (for 2!). The staff was friendly and helpful. We even got free cookies delivered to the room (it was Xmas Eve). The 24-hour Starbucks is a nice plus.Note, you most likely will need a car to enjoy the location. It is about 10 miles off the strip (a 20-minute drive w/o traffic). For us, this was perfect. The proximity to Red Rocks Canyon meant that our days were spent hiking, we'd come back to the hotel to relax, and evenings were spent on the Strip. Safe travels everyone!	
Dec 25 2005	Great off-strip hotel	I stayed one night for free on December 23 with a certificate from Marriott. There was no check-in line, and I got a room with a view of Red Rock Canyon in Palm Tower. The downside is that I had to walk through the casino and past several restaurants to get there. Although rated 4-star in some websites, it certainly has amenities like 5-star hotels. The room is huge. You can choose the size and firmness you like from three different sets of pillows. Two people can get things done more quickly before and after bed with features like separate shower and Jacuzzi, two sets of sinks, separate door for lavatory. I didn't try any restaurants in this hotel, but the casino was smoky and the pay-off for the video poker games wasn't good. By the time I got back my room in the evening, two pieces of chocolate were on my pillow. It wasn't much, but the guesture was just as sweet as the candy. The next morning when I was ready to leave the room, I found a receipt in my door. Following its instruction, I used express checkout by calling and leaving the key in the room, thus saved myself a long walk to the front desk.Over all, this is a very nice and quite place. I feel more like in a Southern California resort than in Vegas. If you like quiteness and luxury and don't mind a 15-20 minutes drive to the strip, this is the place to stay.	
Nov 30 2005	On and Off the Strip	We stayed off the stip this time...at the JW Marriott in Summerlin. The hotel was BEAUTIFUL and the room was spacious and clean. The pools were lovely and service was great.We enjoyed the Celine Dion concert and time off the strip as well. Las Vegas is a great place no matter your age, mood, or financial situation.	
Nov 28 2005	Thanksgiving Holiday Review	This is a review of the Thanksgiving Holiday -reviewing both Las Vegas and the JW Marriott. FYI, I am a travel agent in my early 40s and my boyfriend is an executive in his early 50s. We have stayed just about everywhere in Las Vegas. Wednesday, November 23rdTaxi ride from Bellagio was approx. $32.00. We arrived at 1:30pm and were given a room right away. Easy, quick check-in. The staff was friendly and helpful. Rooms were very nice and large. The best things about the room were 1) you could open the French doors to a walk out balcony therefore letting you have fresh air (unlike strip hotels) and 2) the very large bathroom with a real nice Jacuzzi tub for two and a large shower big enough for two. The hotel is done in a California craftsman/mission style with nice wood touches all over the place. Casino was adequate and large enough. Dining choices were varied and seemed adequate as well. Beds were very comfortable and it was nice to have free bottled water and robes in the room.We had lunch at their Irish pub restaurant which was good and inexpensive. We also had breakfast there on Friday and it was about  the price as room service and less expensive then their 24 hour restaurant. Service was good too. A 24 hour Starbucks was next door.We took advantage of their complimentary shuttle (several times a day) at 5pm and reached Macys - their drop off point at 5:20pm. We walked to Paris to see their We Will Rock You Broadway style show which was very good at 90 minutes long. Note: buy the cheapest tickets as all seats seemed great. We got the most expensive which in hindsight would not have opted for. After that, a little gambling at MGM then back to Macys for the Marriotts last pick up at 11:30pm. Each time we took the shuttle it was on time, precisely.Thursday, November 24thAfter sleeping in and having in-room coffee (bad coffee though) we ventured out to the pool to have lunch. The weather was nice and the pool and Jacuzzi were both working and of perfect temperature. There was no towel Nazis to check your towels out and there were plenty of loungers around the pool. The only disappointment is that for that level of Marriott (JW status) the pool chaises should have cushions on them for comfort. Trying to obtain service at the pool was difficult at first but perhaps they did not plan on having such nice weather on Thanksgiving and were short staffed. We both had enormous Bloody Marys and split a chicken sandwich at the pool. Beware you are paying room service prices at the pool which add $2 per order fee plus, I believe, an 18% service charge added on too. We took the 5pm shuttle again and were dropped off at the pitch black Macys parking lot. We picked up a cab right away and went to THEhotel at Mandalay Bay for some perfect view cocktails at their indoor/outdoor lounge high up overlooking Las Vegas. There was a very nice crowd there. We sat outside on their couches, heat lamps and all and enjoyed some pre-Thanksgiving dinner cocktails. Drinks ran about $12.00 each.We had the Thanksgiving Special dinner at MIX, THEhotel. It was sticker shock as my travel mate did not ask the price when he made reservations. $105.00 per person plus beverages and gratuities. Lots of green for a free range four course turkey dinner. Had I known that I would have opted for the less traditional lobster dinner. Wine list was nice and dinner was good but service was a bit much - way overdone! View was nice and we ate in a pod. You must see the pods for yourself!Full, we took a taxi back to hotel instead of their shuttle. Once we got back we ventured into the casino and lost. Back to bed!Friday, November 25thWe requested late check out as we had a 3pm flight out. They granted it and then we secured their shuttle at $20/per person back to the airport. The tower representative was kind enough to take care of that and then she went on line for us to print out our boarding passes.Check out was easy as well and the airport showed up right on the minute. Hotel SummaryI would recommend this hotel to those who want to get away from the hectic strip and those not minding to take the shuttle at Marriotts appointed time. If you are late nighter - stay on the strip. The hotel is great for families and couples but not for those who like their in-house entertainment. Service was good, rooms were great!	
Nov 28 2005	Best place to stay in Vegas!	We recently stayed at the JW Marriott Las Vegas for the Thanksgiving holiday from Nov.23-26th. We are a family of 4 with 2 toddlers. We've stayed all over Las Vegas and continue to return to the JW because the rooms are spacious, the pool is one of the best in Vegas, we feel welcome with our kids in tow, and the service is spectacular!THE ROOM: We were lucky enough to get a complimentary stay in a 2 bedroom suite in the Palm Tower this trip due to the kindness of one of the Guest Relations Managers. This room was absolutely amazing!!!! It was over 2000 Sq. feet, with a huge master bedroom with king bed, desk and walk in closet, a master bath with seperate rain show and double sinks. There was a second bedroom also with a king bed, it's own bathroom with seperate tub and rain shower too. The entry included a nice bench and led to the bar area with mini fridge, sink area and barstools. There was a dining area with table &amp; chairs for 6, a living area with 2 sofas, a few chairs and a chaise. There are also entertainment centers in each of the rooms, each with a nice TV. There is a small powder room just off of the entry, so you have a total of 3 bathrooms. These rooms are at the far ends of the hallways and they take up the entire length of the hotel end, there is a large verandah that stretches all the way around the room, it has 2 chaises and a table and 4 chairs for lounging or having meals outside. Each room also had it's own seperate thermostat and temperature controls and ceiling fans too. This was the most amazing room we've ever stayed in. The pictures don't do it justice, it was too big to photograph!THE POOL: This pool is huge and heated, it's one of the best pools in Vegas, surrounded by palm trees, waterfalls, cabanas, and plenty of lounge chairs. There are also life guards on duty. You will also find 2 jaccuzis at either end of the pool. The poolside bar is closed at this time of year, but when we've come in the summer they serve great drinks and food at very reasonable prices.THE FOOD: We were given complimentary breakfast buffet at Cerces each morning of our stay. They also have a menu for those of you who don't enjoy a buffet. The buffet includes, pancakes, waffles, omlettes, eggs, sausage, bacon, crepes, blintzs, potatoes, cereals - hot &amp; cold, fruit, lox &amp; bages, pastries, I probably forgot a few things, but it's a really great buffet. We also did room service Thanksgiving morning and had a nice meal out on the verandah. The room service menu is ok, but slightly limited. They do have a nice children't menu and prices are average. We also ventured to the onsite Starbucks several times for hot chocolate, pastries, sandwiches, and chips. There is also an Irish pub onsite, and Japanese, and Italian restaurants. All are located in the Palm Tower except for Cerces which is in the Spa Tower.THE CASINO: We aren't big gamblers, we didn't even venture into the casino this stay. It's small compared to others in Vegas and very smoky, but if you're staying on site it's a nice alternative to the 20 minute drive to the strip.THE SERVICE: Everyone here is so nice, from the valets to housekeeping. This is our favorite place to stay in Vegas, it's nice to be away from the strip and really enjoy your vacation away from the crowds! Give it a try, you won't be disappointed!	
