Aug 29 2005 	An Oasis off the Strip!!	I did not stay at this hotel but my boyfriend was there for a conference while we stayed at the MGM. Since he was busy with meetings all day I decided to come with him and use the pool facilities. The management had no trouble what so ever and was nice enough to add my name to the list so no one would hassle me. When I arrived at the pool area and hotel my breathe was taken. It was gorgeous. Full of palm trees and tropical covered walkways. The pool had enough lounges and cabanas to use. When I asked for a towel I had explained I am not staying there and no questions were asked and I was told to enjoy my visit. In the background was wonderful Hawaaiin music sung by authentic muscisians. The pool is huge and has a great waterfall that you can walk under. Also the casino is a bit smaller but if your willing to travel off the strip the tables are lower and the dealers are willing to explain any card game if they're not busy. Theres tons of evidence that shows how this hotel is rated #1 in Vegas!	
Aug 25 2005	Very refreshing 	First off, if you're looking for the hustle and bustle of the strip, this is not the hotel for you. On the other hand, if you want a nice relaxing experience then this is the hotel for you. I stayed at &quot;The Hotel&quot; at the Mandalay Bay earlier this summer and found out what a joke that place was (doesn't surprise me it's now down to the #3 rating as their service is a joke). I would suggest the employees there take some notes from the Marriott on how 5 Star service should really be. Let's start with the valet. I used it throughout my stay and I think the longest wait was 2 minutes. Upon check-in we were greeted nicely and someone even called up to our room in the first 10 minutes to make sure everything was to our liking. The pool was quite nice and there were cabanas that were reasonably price ($50 for a half day on the weekdays). If you needed an umbrella, you just asked one of the staff and they would put it up for you right over your lounge chair. Ironically, it's nestled in the suburbs and there are tons of stores in the vicinity and some excellent restaurants. We went to Rosemary's (about a ten minute drive) and had one of the best dinners ever. As for the drive to the strip, someone quoted here it took them 4 hours?! I'm not sure what that was about. Unless some tanker flipped over, realistically you're talking about 25 minutes. You simply hop on to Summerlin Pkwy and then over to I95 and you're pretty much on the freeway the entire drive. I think what's happening with some of the posters here is they are taking the surface roads and that's why it's taking so long. Anyway, had a marvelous time and will definitely stay here again.	
Aug 24 2005	Loved This Hotel!!!	This hotel is fantastic. Great way to end a week in Vegas. We spent the week on the strip and moved over to the Marriott for the weekend. We had a car, so getting around was easy. This property is located in a beautiful area of Vegas, with great restaurants and shopping close by, and the strip is only approximately 15 miles away. The staff is wonderful, the rooms are great, and the pool is the best. No crowds to deal with, very relaxing. We truly enjoyed ourselves at the J.W. Marriott, and would definetly recommend this hotel.	
Aug 21 2005 	What a great place for a conference	My 3 friends and I stayed here 4 nights last week for a Nursing conference. What an incredible place-a true 5 star hotel-from the wonderful customer service&amp;clean roomsto the bathrooms you never want to leave. The jacuzzi and the rainfall shower head made it hard to leave each morning, but afterall we did need to attend the conference. You would think that it would be difficult to feed and house 825 nurses, but the JW Marriott rules! Never did it feel crowded nor did we have to stand in line. The food there was outstanding whether it was at the conference or in their 24 hour cafe. I thought being off the Strip would be a challenge for three hard core gamblers and one want-to-be gambler, but the Ramparts Casino was great fun. It certainly kept us occupied when we weren't in one of the many rooms listening to one of our well known speakers. The casino had a variety of slots, most were multi-denomination machines which seem to be the new trend in Vegas. Overall, we all felt these slots were looser than most of the Strips slots.It was very easy to find yourway around this goregous property, from the waterfalls throughout the property to the enormous pool-which by the way was not crowded. The pool has a waterfall that provides you with a free back and shoulder massage if you stand directly underneath it. There is a small restaurant with poolside service provided- the food here was also fabulous.To be honest, I can't think of one thing that was negative except it will be difficult to stay in another hotel that doesn't add up to the JW Marriott!	
Aug 20 2005	Excellent place to relax after the strip	After three nights in Ballys on the strip the JW Marriott was a revelation. Although there was no room available when we arrived at 3PM my wife and I were offered free passes to the spa for the duration of our stay - excellent facilities. The rooms are absolutely massive and luxurious. Wonderful view of the mountains and nice choice of air conditioning or fan. Was nice to turn air conditioning off for once. The bathrooms are amazing, including the rain room and jacuzzi. Try the bathrobes - very nice. Most people seemed to agree as they were walking around the pool in them. The pool is fantastic. Good service, plenty of space to relax. You couldn't actually swim in the pool - too shallow/busy but was ideal to cool off. Water coolers available around the pool. The restaurants/bars on site are good. We enjoyed nice food at the Italian restaurant and Irish pub. The buffet is huge but we hated it but not because of the food but theconcept. We have never seen people waste so much food - horrific. The only downside is the cost of transfers. Expect to pay 40 dollars from the strip in a taxi. The hotel did offer to pick us up from the Fashion Mall for free but we did not fancy taking our bags up the strip mid afternoon. One complaint was airport transfers. We were happy to see that the hotel provides a shuttle to the aiport hourly from 5am. However this does cost 20 dollars per person. We thought this was a little unnecessary given the fact that they provide a free shuttle to the strip!!! Overall excellent.	
Aug 16 2005	An oasis in the wild world of Las Vegas	After 2 frantic days on the strip at New York, New York, it was a pleasure to spend 5 nights at the J.W. Marriott. This resort is an oasis in the wild world of Las Vegas. The pool area was excellent, the staff was pleasant and our room was large and well-appointed, with a great bathroom and super shower. The Italian restaurant served terrific food, and the Irish pub was great fun. The casino is low key, but there are plenty of machines and table games to keep players occupied. Obviously, my experience differed from that of other recent reviewers, but this is our third visit, and we have always had positive experiences. It is important for prospective guests to understand that this is a relatively quiet and elegant resort, located 20 minutes west of the Strip. A car is necessary to enjoy being in this location. (Check out Red Rock Canyon for a great day outdoors.) If this is the type of vacation environment that you are looking for, the J.W. Marriott is the right choice.	
