 was treated. I feel the night staff needs to be trained in handling situations such as mine. I feel the woman I spoke to needs to be told she can not treat someone rude because they did not pay top dollar to stay at the JW Vegas. We made the decision to check out Saturday afternoon and stay at a hotel on the strip that we always stay when we come to Vegas... they treat us very well! I stayed at the JW in Arizona with my girlfriends last year and we had inpecable service and a wonderful stay. Unfortunitely, I can not say that about the JW vegas. It's very upsetting to be treated terribly when you go out of your way to see that everything is set before you arrive and to be told in so many words, if you would have paid top dollar you'd recieve better service at the JW vegas. RE: Aquae Sulis Spa:We enjoyed our service!! The two ladies who gave us our couple message we're great! I also wanted to mention the spa manager who helped to find my earrings I lost at the SPA on Saturday... she delivered them herself to me after we had checked out and after her shift, to our strip hotel. I feel she went above and beyond! She truely is a great employee!!  I know this is an experience I won't forget due to the rude comments. I read the great reviews on Tripadvisor.com about the jw vegas and thought I made the best choice because of my great experience at the JW in arizona, but I was wrong. I will return to the JW Arizona with my family because the rooms, service and staff are top notch. Unfortunitely, I would not recommend the jw vegas to anyone... 1. it's too far from strip2. the carpet and furniture need to be replaced 3. yes the bathrooms are great but how long are you really in your bathroom? 4. the grounds are beautiful5. the casino is like being on a river boat in Illinois, not like a VEGAS strip hotel feel at all.6. night service staff is rudeLesson learned... Stick with the what you know... stay at the strip hotels, they are the BEST!	
May 4 2005	JW Las Vegas Rocks!	Just got back from a week stay at JW from 4/23-4/30. The Hotel is magnificent. The grounds are beautiful, especially pool area. Stayed for free using Marriott Rewards Points. Notwithstanding this, we were given a great room on the 6th (top) floor of Spa Tower overlooing the mountains. The room was large, but the bathroom was huge! Marble everywhere. Basic decorations but plenty of room for a family of four. Ate in Ceres Restaurant for breakfast. They have a great and reasonable ($13.95 adults, 7.95 kids) breakfast buffet. Many selections to choose from. Food at Poolside Cafe also quite good and reasonable. Casino was typical. Not too lavish and a little smoky. My husband and I went for a 50 minute massage. ($100 plus $18.00 tip). The Spa is truely lovely. Seperate workout area (must pay $20/day if not receving a treatment). The massages were great and they have a nice area to shower, change, etc. with all of the amenities you could possibly want. Spa also has seperate whirlpools, outdoor pools and relaxing areas. Trip to Strip (went evey day) took 15-20 minutes max. Nice to stay off trip and just &quot;visit&quot;. You can valet park at all hotels for free. Just $1 tip for valet. Saw Mystere at TI. Great show for all ages. Also saw Mama Mia at Mirage. Also very good. Highlight of trip was a helicopter tour of the grand canyon (used Look Tours). Trip went from downtown Las Vegas over Hoover Dam and Lake Mead and through entire canyon. Stopped at a ranch for a cowboy breakfast and horseback ride before return trip down the stip. Cannot say enough how great it was! My entire family cannot stop talking about it. Well worth the money. Can't wait to return to Vegas and the JW.	
May 2 2005	10th Anniversary Trip -- Great time	Just got back from our 10th wedding anniversary trip. First time staying the the JW Marriott. Wife doesn't like the smokey Vegas strip hotels and we were looking for more of a spa experience, so went with the JW. Got the AAA package with breakfast included both nights ($238/night rate). Very pleased with the hotel. It's only about 5-10 minutes away from the strip and has a wonderful golf resort feel to it. Very well landscaped, lush grounds, nice architecture. Not too crowded at all, saw some leisure and some business travelers. Hardly any smoke, even in the Rampart casino in the evenings.Stayed in the standard room and it was quite nice. Tons of room, almost looked like it was missing some furniture since there was so much space. Still had a &quot;Marriott&quot; feel, neutral wallpaper and carpet looked a little older. Not quite comparable to the suite at Caesar's Palace tower, but much better than your average Vegas room. Very comfortable king bed, ceiling fan, large walk-in closet with convenient electronic safe and two robes. Bathroom was huge, with whirlpool tub for 2 (sort of a &quot;peanut&quot; shape), shower with rainfall, granite vanity. The &quot;cooler&quot; fridge was useless, but there was free bottled water. Room was in the Palm Tower which was a bit of a walk from the spa and Ceres restaurant for breakfast, but really not too far. Each tower has its own valet parking (free for guests) and check-in desk which was convenient. We stayed on the 6th (top) floor and had a beautiful view from the french doors. No real balcony to step onto, but it looks like the suites might have balconies with chairs. Service overall was very good. Friendly, courteous staff. Greeted us by name when we called for a wake up call (yes, it shows on their computer but it's a nice touch anyway). Spent most of Saturday in the Aquae Solis Spa. Booked massage for me, European facial, manicure and pedicure for my wife. Spa area is very nice, separate facilities for men and women, but a common area in the back between with a private pool and jaccuzzi for spa guests only. Very intimate setting, mostly couples or women. Ordered lunch from the room service menu and had it delivered to the spa pool in back, only took about 30 minutes. The waterfall shower was intense, decent jaccuzzi, cold plunge, steam and dry sauna and lots of lounging area to just relax. Also free juices, citrus water and fruit.Had dinner on the strip at Bobby Flay's Mesa Grill in Caesar's. Wonderful food, excellent service, great atmosphere. Highly recommend the roasted corn tamale with shrimp appetizer and the signature pork tenderloin. Decided to come back to the hotel and play at the Rampart Casino Saturday night since the strip table limits were $15+ everywhere and couldn't find an open table on a Saturday night. Rampart was great, $5 minimums. Took a few minutes to get a seat, but dealers were friendly and the players seemed to be having a good time overall. Not too smoky either compared to the strip. Played till about 2:00 am and noticed a lot fewer people after midnight, must be a lot of locals. Breakfast was included and was the breakfast buffet at Ceres. Excellent food, lots of fresh fruit and pastries, omelettes, eggs and waffles made to order, usual selection of bacon, sausage, potatoes, cereals, lox, cream cheese, bagels, fresh squeezed OJ and good coffee. Good service too. Ours was free, but the bill for two would have been about $30 including tax. Ceres is surrounded by some waterfalls and you can sit outside if you'd like.Overall had a great experience and would definitely stay again. Really liked the resort feel and the lack of smoke. Would be good for couples or families. Saw a lot of weddings going on there also. Main pool area looked very nice, want to go back again to use that. Close enough to pop down to the Strip for shows, sights, dining, etc. but still far enough away to relax. Note: we had a car which I'd strongly recommend if you want to go to the Strip.	
May 1 2005	One of the best	First, let me explain that I am not employed by Marriott, I am completely independent and stayed there with my wife and daughter on vacation.It is very obvious that not just money, but a lot of time, care and attention has been put into the detail of this hotel. Fixtures &amp; fittings and build quality are superb.The hotel has a fantastic landscaped garden with streams and fish ponds, a large swimming pool, hot tub, loungers and relaxing piped background music. It's hard to imagine this was built in a desert.We had a huge room with two queen beds, a large bathroom with 'his and hers' wash basins, double sized jacusi bath, walk in glass fronted marble clad shower with rain effect shower head as well as a normal power shower. Beware, there are full height wall mirrors in the bath area.The bedroom also boasted a balcony overlooking the mountains and desert, a walk in cloak room, large screen TV, coffee making facilities and mini bar.Breakfast consisted of a self service hot and cold food buffet, fresh fruit, danish pastries etc, etc, etc all washed down with far too much coffee and orange juice. A chef was there to cook eggs in the way of our choice. The catering staff go the extra mile, even so far as hand carving mellon decorations. Don't go to breakfast if on a diet!There is a small business suite located in the Consierge area, containing PCs, a printer and a photo copier.The hotel operates a regular shuttle bus service to the strip which takes about 20 minutes.We wondered why the hotel was to quiet, that was until we explored the long corridors and came across the casino. That's where everyone was hiding.Apparently some people enjoy sitting in a windowless, smoke filled room, pumping money into money grabbing machines. The casino area is a mini village in its own right, containing food outlets, bars and small shops. All I can say is it was considerate of them to allow us to use the superb hotel facilities in peace.The staff complimented the magnificence of the hotel perfectly. All staff were friendly from check in clerk to groundsman. No stuffiness or snootines.Let's hope these high standards are maintained.	
Apr 13 2005	Loved It!!!	We've stayed at many 3-5 star Hotels since Mar 2004. We have not found anything as nice or as classy as JW Marriotts. We are still talking about that resort. I'd highly recommend it to anyone. We look forward to going back.	
Apr 9 2005	The best in Vegas	Stayed at the Monte Carlo on the strip for 4 nights prior to moving out to the JW Marriott for 5 nights. Picked the Monte Carlo for location and being mid-priced. For us, 4 nights on the Strip is more than plenty and we looked forward to moving to somewhere more relaxed for the second half of our holiday. We booked it based solely on tripadvisor recommendations and were not disappointed.Firstly location. Yes it is about 20 mins from the Strip. So if all your activities centre around there, then this may not be the best spot for you. However, it is not a difficult journey to get down there. You just turn right out of the hotel onto Rampart and then keep going until you turn left on to the road that will deposit you on the right part of Las Vegas Blvd. For us, mostly Sahara (about 4 blocks from memory) then you keep on going until you hit the Strip.Upside is that Summerlin is a world away from the hussle and bussle and great for getting out into the hills. Red Rock Canyon is minutes away and it is well located for the 95 and 215 if you want to go elsewhere outside Vegas.The hotel itself is set in its own, well maintained gardens and grounds. There is no road noise, no sense of air pollution and the views of the hills are just great.ReceptionWe arrived and went to check in at the Spa Tower. there were two receptionists on duty and we were seen within a few minutes. We arrived early at 11.00 but were given a room for immediate occupation. We had a ground floor room in the Palms Tower, looking out across towards the hills. We got back in the car and drove around to the other tower and used the free Valet Parking. Car parked, bags brought to room without any delay. Used the Valet parking all the time we were there. Extremely friendly and helpful with directions and advice. We had hired an open top Mustang and they would put the top up and down for us when we came and went without needing to be asked.The Room.I have noted a couple of people saying the rooms looked tired, or other less than complimentary comments about the rooms. So, I am very happy to report that this was not the case. You enter the room via a marble floored hallway, with the bathroom off to the right. It contains a two seater whirlpool bath and seperate shower unit, with standard wall shower or overhead rain head shower. There is a seperate WC accessed from within the bathroom. Lots of good quality product in the bathroom, although I don't recall it having any special name (but I am a guy).Back into the corridor and you next pass a walk in closet on your right with safe, ironing board and iron and plenty of hanging space for clothes.The corridor then opens out into one of the largest bedrooms I have seen in a hotel. Ahead of you is a standard TV/Drawer unit and beyond that a desk and 2 chairs. To the right is a king size bed (extremely comfortable) and a sofa and an armchair. There is also a round coffee table. the opening double patio doors looked out onto the hills and made the room bright and airy. The room has a modern air con unit with digital display mounted on the wall. It also has a large ceiling fan and over head light, both working on variable slider switches so you can set them just so. Wallpaper, carpets, fittings in first rate condition. No signs of wear and tear at all.Room Service.We had beakfast brought to the room on a couple of days. it is delivered on a wheeled table, with winged sections that are expanded to make a large dining table. We had it placed in front of the patio doors so we could take in the view. What I liked about Room Service was that the prices were reasonable and you did not feel you were being ripped off. Can't remember exact prices in the Monte Carlo, just a feeling that you would NOT want to pay that much. I think Champagne worked out at less than half the price of the Monte Carlo.The public areas inside the hotel.The whole place has a very open, airy and chilled out feel to it. There is plenty of marble in the lobbies and corridors connecting the two towers, with high celings and wide passageways. Maybe the feeling is enhanced because we moved away from the Strip and all the crowds, but it feels tranquil. In fact that's a word that a lot of people there was using to describe it, a sort of oasis in the desert.We ate in the Japanese restaurant one evening. Service was good and attentive. Not had much experience of Japanese food, but everything seemed well prepared and was certainly fresh and tasty. There is also a sushi bar in there and they also do Taipan table preparation.We had a lunch and an evening snack in the Irish pub. Good simple straight forward food with an Irish slant. They also pulled an exceptional pint of Guinness. The evening we went in, there was a live band playing. Mostly good, but one of the singers hit a few bum notes. However this was made up for in enthusiasm and energy. In fact, your typical pub entertainment. Staff friendly and some were actually Irish, coming from an area less than 20 miles away from my wife's parents village over in Ireland.Next door to the Irish pub is a Starbucks, open 24 hours. Your room key gets you a a free size upgrade on your drinks there.We had drinks in the Ceres lounge. Large comfy chairs and sofas and attentive staff. We did not eat there.We had a breakfast in the cafe which faces on to the casino floor on our last morning. (We had come down at a time when the buffet place was closed, probably switching from breakfast to lunch?). They ask if you want to sit smoking or non-smoking, but as the place opens out into the casino, you don't get a lot of choice.We also had a meal in the casino's 'fine dining' restaurant. I can't recall its name and had a very average dining experience. we ate at 8pm and when it came to desserts, got the definate impression they wanted to pack up early and get off home. I believe the casino and this place is under different management than the hotel itself.We also had some drinks and snacks at the pool side bar. Friendly and attentive staff. Never found the time to use the pool, but it looked very inviting. there were also plenty of cabanas dotted about if you wanted to make a day of it.Summary.Oned of the nicest, friendliest and most comfortable places I have stayed. A true oasis but so close to vegas. If you are hiring a car, then getting around will not be a problem. You will be able to dip into Strip as and when you want but more importantly, escape from it!	
