Oct 31 2004	So relaxing	Having spent the first 4 days of our Vegas trip at the Aladdin and doing the strip thing, we were ready for a relaxing next 5 days. We stayed Friday 1st - Wednesday 6th October. Only about 10 minutes drive out of town, pulled up at the Valet and was greeted by a very happy valet guy. He looked after the car while we checked in. The whole place was very quiet and relaxed. There was one person at reception, and tbh that's all it warranted, it was a very unobtrusive feel to the place. Checked in. Caused a nightmare because I have 4 different reservations for the 5 nights. One of the companies had screwed up and booked 2 beds for one night, as opposed to one bed for 2 nights. She said not to worry and was fine about it all. We were over at the other tower, so back to Valet. Guy opened car doors for us and away we went. Pulled up at the other valet and the guy helped u out with our bags and took car of the car. Room was on the 1st floor and was massive. It overlooked the little river/waterfall that seems to run throught the whole complex. Bed was huge. In the UK we have normal double beds, there I dont think I could even reach out and find my other half. Walk in wardrobe and gorgeous bathroom. It was all soo clean and in A1 condition. Even though there were 3 weddings during our time there, there was never any noise. Pool was lovely but not at all crowded. Valets remembered who we were and where we were from. Its a great position to go off to red rock canyon, and to get back on the interstate. PF Chang, Banana republic and Gap just down the road along with the usual Target and 7/11. The hot tub by the pool, well 2 of them, were open 24 hours a day and were a great size. Free USA Today on weekdays outside your room. Only went in the casino once for the toilet!! Now for the food. Having had breakfast at Paris while on the strip, I dont think any buffet can compare to that. There is no breakfast buffet but lunch starts at 11am so thats no problem as we got up late most of the time. Food was a lot cheaper than the strip but wasnt as good, as Paris. However waitresses were very helpful, there was also a bit of a queue. Sunday, they do a champagne brunch with crab and fresh seafood. In the UK 1kg of prawns cost about $30 in supermarkets, so I took full advantage of the food. I think it was about $13 for champagne brunch. Food was really the only let down, if they got the buffet a bit better (its still on par with say the mirage) they would be 100% there I reckon. Also, one thing to note, we were in our mid twenties and the average age eating in the buffet was of retirement age. I dont care but some people may prefer to be with a younger crowd, altho by the pool everyone was about 30-40 age group. My dad cannot wait to go to Vegas now and check out this hotel.	
